Both required outputs are written. Summary of what I did:

**Analysis** — Ran 25 iterations of propose-test-refine on the 50,000-patient ds001_nsclc cohort (overall ORR = 16.9%). Tested 34 hypotheses with 33 analyses spanning univariate screens of all 77 binary, 42 continuous, and 4 categorical features; ECOG- and lab-marker dose-response curves; pairwise and three-way interactions; race/insurance disparities; and a final adjusted multivariable logistic regression.

**Key findings**
- **Strongest main effects (signed, all confirmed adjusted, p<0.001)**: feature_051 (ECOG-like, monotonic 21%→11%), feature_013 (-), feature_067 (-), feature_011 (-, monotonic), feature_099 (albumin-like, +), feature_063 (-).
- **Signature interaction**: feature_092 (PD-L1-like) × the triple combination of feature_006/007/039 — ORR doubles to 33% only when all four conditions are met (interaction coef +0.876, p<1e-22). Neither the regimen nor the biomarker alone moves ORR.
- **PD-L1 × smoking direction reversal**: PD-L1 effect OR=1.33 in former smokers but OR=0.72 in never-smokers (p=0.024).
- **Health-disparity signals**: Asian × Medicaid is the most disadvantaged subgroup (ORR 12.6%, OR=0.64, p=0.005). Insurance gap (private > Medicaid) survives clinical adjustment; racial differences do not.
- **Null findings**: age (feature_078), hemoglobin-like feature_014, NLR-like feature_066 all NS.

